{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509857"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:20:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:20:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11450"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11450"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.09,0.47,0.27,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4084"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53447"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4084"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11450"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38913"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"1491"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4935"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6032"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8727"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11473"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15279"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42603"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43227"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53447"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old man on a spinal rehabilitation ward requires review due to sudden significant hypertension of 200/120 mmHg (usually 130/70 mmHg). Upon investigation, the patient states he has episodic diaphoresis, a pounding headache and is very anxious about his new symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a history of asthma, eczema and presumed sepsis from a urinary tract infection a year ago. He had a motor vehicle accident four months ago, which led to a transection of the T4 spinal cord. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring his physical examination, the patient has a low body temperature, goosebumps on his thighs and lower legs, and a bradycardia. His bladder is not distended and he has a functioning indwelling catheter. The initial steps are to raise the patient\u0027s head, lower his legs and remove any restrictive clothing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Unblock the catheter","Aperients","GTN patch","Amlodipine","Antibiotics"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient\u0027s spinal cord trauma and sudden presentation of symptoms and signs, it is highly likely he has developed autonomic dysreflexia. Autonomic dysreflexia (also known as autonomic hyperreflexia) is a medical emergency that affects individuals with a spinal cord injury typically at the level of T6 or above. Sympathetic nervous system stimulation below the level of the spinal cord injury leads to widespread vasoconstriction of splanchnic blood vessels, resulting in severe hypertension (due to the release of substances such as noradrenaline). Once sensed by the aortic arch and carotid body baroreceptors, parasympathetic activity above the level of the lesion occurs, causing compensatory bradycardia, but the inhibitory brainstem impulses fail to travel below the lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDelayed treatment of autonomic dysreflexia can lead to many serious complications, including stroke, seizures, pulmonary oedema, myocardial infarction and death. Common causes typically involve the urinary system (distended bladder, UTI, kidney stones), bowels (constipation, impaction, haemorrhoids, or gaseous distension), skin (burns, tight clothing, infection), and other causes, including fracture, sexual intercourse, labour or severe menstrual cramping.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment of autonomic dysreflexia involves the reversal of any acute causes and if required pharmacological control of hypertension. Blood pressure and pulse can rapidly fluctuate in autonomic dysreflexia, so reversible anti-hypertensives (e.g\u003Cstrong\u003E. GTN\u003C/strong\u003E) are preferred. Alternatively, if a GTN patch, spray, or tablet is not available or contraindicated, then an alternative short-acting antihypertensive agent, such as captopril or nifedipine, can be used. Since a cause for the patient\u0027s autonomic dysreflexia is not easily identified in this case, the best option is the application of a GTN patch. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf a cause is suspected, then alternative treatments should be initiated. If a blocked catheter is suspected, then \u003Cstrong\u003Eunblocking the catheter\u003C/strong\u003E and irrigating the bladder are required. This is not suspected in this patient, as his bladder is not distended, and the indwelling catheter is functional.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf faecal impaction is suspected, then a local anaesthetic and manual decompaction or administration of \u003Cstrong\u003Eaperients\u003C/strong\u003E may alleviate the cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine \u003C/strong\u003E(or other calcium channel blockers) is typically used to treat hypertension, but due to its \u0027time to effect\u0027 being approximately eight hours, GTN is a better choice in this context (time to effect is within a few minutes). If the patient become hypotensive, then amlodipine cannot be easily reversed, whereas a GTN patch can be easily removed. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibiotic\u003C/strong\u003E treatment may be useful in treating bacterial causes of autonomic dysreflexia, such as a UTI. However, this patient does not have a fever, and a UTI is not suspected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Autonomic dysreflexia is a medical emergency involving high sympathetic stimulation leading to hypertension and blockage of compensatory parasympathetic stimulation below the level of a spinal cord injury.","Raising the patient\u0027s head, lowering his legs, and removing restrictive clothing, are the initial steps for treatment of autonomic dysreflexia","If a cause for a patient\u0027s autonomic dysreflexia is not easily identified, the initial treatment should be the application of a GTN patch."],"references":["NSW Agency for Clinical Innovation. Treatment of autonomic dysreflexia for adults and adolescents with spinal cord injuries: A guide for clinicians in non-specialist units. Sydney: ACI; 2024. Available online at ; https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/155149/ACI-Treatment-of-autonomic-dysreflexia-for-adults-and-adolescents-with-spinal-cord-injuries.pdf","Allen KJ, Leslie SW. Autonomic Dysreflexia. [Updated 2022 Feb 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482434/","Faulkner JK, McGibney D, Chasseaud LF, Perry JL, Taylor IW, 1986. The pharmacokinetics of amlodipine in healthy volunteers after single intravenous and oral doses and after 14 repeated oral doses given once daily. Br J Clin Pharmacol. 22(1):21-25. doi:10.1111/j.1365-2125.1986.tb02874.x"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38913"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11450"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemR